Dear Hiring Team,

It is with great pleasure that I submit my candidacy for the *AI Engineer (RL & WBC)* role with *Foundation*. I bring over three years of professional experience in machine learning, deep learning, and AI systems engineering, along with a strong academic foundation as a Master of Science in Computer Science graduate from Pace University, NY.

Through my experience across two engineering roles, I have built and delivered production-grade ML systems that directly reflect the technical depth this position demands — specifically in reinforcement learning, distributed training, and real-time policy execution. As a Software Engineer at Sperse, I architected a concurrent multi-agent orchestration system using LangGraph and LangChain with reinforcement learning-inspired reward shaping for tool-call routing, enabling real-time policy execution across 1,000+ platform endpoints with hardware-in-the-loop safety constraints — directly analogous to locomotion policy dispatch in humanoid robots. To keep these systems production-ready, I implemented a full observability stack using LangSmith covering tracing, structured logging, and evaluation hooks, and optimized deep learning inference via PyTorch-backed prompt routing, reducing end-to-end latency by 60% and LLM API costs by 50% through distributed training of routing policies. Prior to Sperse, as a Software Engineer at Qualitest, I designed a cloud-agnostic Storage Service using Python, PostgreSQL, and Redis handling real-time control of distributed I/O across AWS S3, Google Cloud Storage, and MinIO, and developed AWS Step Functions workflows to orchestrate long-running jobs via event-driven state machine control — patterns directly analogous to hardware-in-the-loop validation. Together, these roles have prepared me to contribute meaningfully to Foundation's RL training pipelines, sim2real transfer workflows, and real-time control systems for the Phantom humanoid platform.

My academic research experience has given me a rigorous foundation in GPU-accelerated model development, curriculum learning, and domain randomization — skills that translate directly into the engineering discipline Foundation's small, highly-technical teams value. As an AI Researcher at the Pace Artificial Intelligence Lab, I conducted deep learning research using PyTorch, CUDA, and LoRA on Pace University's high-performance computing cluster, applying curriculum learning and domain randomization to improve policy generalization across distributions — techniques I understand are directly transferable to sim2real transfer and locomotion policy training for humanoid robots. I managed the full training-to-serving lifecycle with CI/CD pipelines and unit testing for reproducible, production-grade delivery. Beyond building the systems myself, I led workshops on GPU programming with CUDA and AI Agents with LangChain and LangGraph for 50+ students — translating complex reinforcement learning and distributed training concepts clearly, which mirrors the knowledge-sharing culture Foundation values in small, collaborative teams.

I deeply believe that building general-purpose humanoid robots to address the labor shortage and reduce human risk in conflict zones and labor-intensive industries is the most important mission for humanity right now — and that it needs to happen yesterday. I would love to contribute my talent to deploying 10,000 robots in 2026 and beyond. I can be reached at #ph or #eml. Thank you for your time and consideration — I look forward to connecting!

